Data Mining on Web Analytics Data

Published Public Link on Rbubs - http://rpubs.com/rohitgossain/data-mining-web-analytics

Introduction and Background

E-commerce companies are collecting large amount of data related to user journey from product discovery to product purchase confirmation. Customers make lot of decisions in between the process and due to ever increase in understanding of statistical models and data technology, companies are trying best to understand their customer behavior.

Hence, we are trying to solve similar problem to understand customer behavior with the help of applications of data mining. We have collected various key metrics of the purchasers from one of the e-commerce company such as their identification ids, their transaction ids, products ids and number of units they bought, visits, total page views, total product views and how many times they added the products in cart.

We have divided the customer behavior into three major sections

  1. Understanding key business metrics and customer purchase pattern.
  2. Segmenting customers based on their browsing pattern and purchase pattern.
  3. Building Regression Model to predict number of units, customer can purchase based on their browsing behavior.

Initially, it is important to include all required R libraries to start the process of building model. Key metrics data has been collected by hitting Adobe Analytics API using company credentials which is masked under .Renviron file. This is only possible through Adobe Analytics R package called RSiteCatalyst built by Randy Zwitch.

Building and Understanding Customer Segments.

it is very important to segment customers based on their similarity and dissimilarity within their browsing and purchase pattern.

#Data Preparation for Clustering (Understanding Customers Segments)
user_profile <- QueueRanked(rs,
                            date.from = '2016-11-24',
                            date.to = '2017-02-05',
                            elements = c('evar48'),
                            metrics = c('units','visits','event2','pageviews','cartadditions'),
                            top = c(10000, 50),
                            interval.seconds = 120)
[1] "Requesting URL attempt #1"
[1] "Requesting URL attempt #2"
[1] "Received ranked report."
df_user <- user_profile[,c("name","units","visits","event2","pageviews","cartadditions")]
r <- with(df_user, which(df_user$name == "::unspecified::"))
df_user <- df_user[-r,]
df_user <- df_user %>% distinct(name, .keep_all = TRUE)
rownames(df_user) <- df_user[,1]
df_user$name <- NULL
names(df_user) <- c("unitsbought", "visits","productviews","pageviews","cartadditions")
head(df_user,20)

Optimal Number of Clusters

To start with, we need to see how many clusters/segments can be possible within available data sets. We have used Elbow method to find optimal number of segments. Based on the Elbow’s plot, 2 or 4 are the best number of clusters and we have chosen 3 as average optimal number of segments.

#Number of clusters using Elbow method
fviz_nbclust(df_user, kmeans, method = "wss") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 3, linetype = 2)

K-means algorithm

After running k-means clustering method, we have seen maximum number of data points are part of cluster 2 and lowest number of data points comes under cluster 1 and 3. But based on their properties, all of them has their own significance in solving business problems.

Analysis and Recommendations

Segment 1/Cluster 1 consists of very few customer ids with kind of abnormal browsing and purchase pattern. They look like outliers who bought many product items and it is very much required for the company to verify their identity. It is quite possible they are part of technical team who are doing live testing on the platform, or some scammers who buying excess of product items and selling them in black market.

Segment3/Cluster 3 consist of subset of customer ids who are very active on website but they are not purchasing much. There is very high cart abandonment rate here and company can do further analysis to find the reason of it. We can call this customer segment as researcher and with right marketing campaign, we can make them to buy products.

Segment2/Cluster2 consists of large customer ids who has idle browsing and purchase pattern. They are visiting right number of pages and product views, adding right number of products in their cart and purchasing them with minimal cart abandonment rate. Out of average 5 visits, they are seeing 20 products and ending up buying 4 of them.

Hierarchical Clustering

Correlation and Covariance

It is important to find the correlation between all given data points, and based on correlation analysis output, there is no correlation between units bought with any of the data points such as visits, product views, page views and cart additions.

#Regression to find out variables which are dependent on customers who bought the products
#Understanding Correlation and Covariance
cor <- cor(df_user, use="complete.obs", method="kendall") 
cov <- cov(df_user, use="complete.obs")
corrplot(cor, method="circle")

Feature Selection and Regression Model

Since, we are going to run regression model, it is important to select right independent variable and hence here we run Stepwise Model path algorithm to find optimal Model based on given initial model. There is no change in Final Model and it is better to include all independent variables for regression modeling.

#Feature Selection

Understanding Regression Model and Analysis

Based on P values (P<0.05), every predictor in the model is significant. Hence our dependent variable, depends on all four predictors. Based on regression coefficient, with increase in 1 unit of visits and page views, units bought will increase by 0.017 and 0.033 units. In addition, with increase in 1 unit of product views and cart addition, units bought will decrease by -0.06 and -0.02 units respectively. This is because, we have seen in analysis report - if user is seeing more and more product views that does not meet he will buy the product. There is a higher chance that he is just a researcher and part of Cluster/Segment 3.

Based on Residual vs Fitted graph, we have can see that there is no linear relationship between dependent and independent variables. Since we are trying to model user behavior, it is not possible that they will have linear relationship.

Graph 2 shows our residual is normally distributed and due to few outliers in the models, it is getting deviated in the end.

Graph 3 shows our residuals has not equally spread, it is again due to few major outliers in the model.

Graph 4 proves our hypothesis towards outliers, outliers are influential in linear regression analysis.

Recommendations

We have tried to build predictive regression model on user behavior data and it is really tough to show user psychology behind shopping pattern using mathematical equation. Our analysis has shown lot of outliers which are part of cluster 1 and cluster 3 but has their own significance in terms of understanding few higher spenders or researches. It is better to build model on cluster 2 which is stable customers and their behavior is an idle behavior, and it is quite possible it will come up with more better results. But we can’t ignore our outliers because we are quite interested in understanding them as well because they can be threat or an opportunity for the business.
